{{Distinguish-otheruses|Cannon|Cannon (disambiguation)}}
The '''Great Cannon of China''' is an [[cyberweapon|attack tool]] that is used to launch [[Denial-of-service attack#Distributed attack|distributed denial-of-service attack]]s on websites by [[Man-in-the-middle attack|intercepting]] massive amounts of [[web traffic]] and redirecting them to targeted websites.<ref name="NYT-China-Said-to-Use-Powerful-New-Weapon-Censor-Internet">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/11/technology/china-is-said-to-use-powerful-new-weapon-to-censor-internet.html | title=China Is Said to Use Powerful New Weapon to Censor Internet | publisher=The New York Times Company | work=The New York Times | date=April 10, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Perlroth, Nicole}}</ref> According to the researchers at the [[Citizen Lab]], the [[International Computer Science Institute]], and [[Princeton University]]'s Center for Information Technology Policy, who coined the term, the Great Cannon hijacks foreign web traffic intended for Chinese websites and re-purposes them to flood targeted [[web servers]] with enormous amounts of traffic in an attempt to disrupt their operations. While it is co-located with the [[Great Firewall]], the Great Cannon is "a separate offensive system, with different capabilities and design."<ref name="China-Great-Cannon">{{cite web | url=https://citizenlab.org/2015/04/chinas-great-cannon/ | title=China's Great Cannon | publisher=Munk School of Global Affairs, University of Toronto, Canada | work=The Citizen Lab | date=April 10, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Marczak, Bill | author2=Weaver, Nicolas | author3=Dalek, Jakub | author4=Ensafi, Roya | author5=Fifield, David | author6=McKune, Sarah | author7=Rey, Arn | author8=Scott-Railton, John | author9=Deibert, Ronald |author10=Paxson, Vern}}</ref>

Besides launching denial-of-service attacks, the tool is also capable of monitoring web traffic<ref name="Motherboard-Great-Cannon-China-Powerful-New-Hacking-Weapon">{{cite web | url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/the-great-cannon-is-chinas-powerful-new-hacking-weapon | title=The 'Great Cannon' is China's Powerful New Hacking Weapon | publisher=Vice Media LLC | work=Motherboard - Vice | date=April 10, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Franceschi-Bicchierai, Lorenzo}}</ref> and distributing [[malware]] in targeted attacks in ways that are similar to the [[Tailored Access Operations#QUANTUM attacks|Quantum Insert]] system used by the U.S. [[National Security Agency]].<ref name="China-Great-Cannon-Lets-Internet-Censors-Hack-Sites-Abroad">{{cite web | url=http://www.ibtimes.com/chinas-great-cannon-lets-internet-censors-hack-sites-abroad-just-ask-github-1877180 | title=China's 'Great Cannon' Lets Internet Censors Hack Sites Abroad -- Just Ask GitHub | publisher=IBT Media Inc. | work=International Business Times | date=April 10, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Stone, Jeff}}</ref>

The first known targets of the Great Cannon (in late March 2015) were websites hosting censorship-evading tools, including [[GitHub]], a web-based code hosting service, and [[GreatFire]], a service monitoring blocked websites in China.<ref name="WSP-China-Deploys-New-Weapon-Online-Censorship-Great-Cannon">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2015/04/10/china-escalates-censorship-efforts-with-debut-of-offensive-cyber-weapon-researchers-say/ | title=China deploys new weapon for online censorship in form of 'Great Cannon' | publisher=The Washington Post | date=April 10, 2015 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Peterson, Andrea}}</ref>

