{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}} {{Infobox magazine | title = Novynar | image_file = | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = | editor = | editor_title = | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = News magazine | frequency = Weekly | circulation = | publisher = | founder = | founded = | firstdate = August 2007 | finaldate = 2008 | company = KP Media | country = [[Ukraine]] | based = [[Kiev]] | language = [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] | website = | issn = | oclc = 176064896 }}
'''''Novynar''''' (meaning ''Newsmaker'' in English)<ref>{{cite web|author1=Oleksandr Sushko|author2=Olena Prystayko|title=Nations in Transit. Ukraine.|url=http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4d53f02713.pdf|work=REF World|accessdate=26 November 2014|date=2010}}</ref> was a [[Ukrainian language]] [[news magazine]] briefly published in [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]], from 2007 to 2008.
==History and profile== ''Novynar'' was first published in August 2007.<ref name=cc>{{cite news|title=KP Media Announces Launch of New Ukrainian-Language News Magazine|url=http://concorde.ua/en/research/daily/4433/|accessdate=26 November 2014|work=Concerde Capital|date=16 August 2007}}</ref> The website was also launched in the same date.<ref name=cc/> It was established as a quality alternative to [[Russian language]] news magazines in the country.<ref name=bne/>
The magazine was part of the KP Media which also owned ''[[Kyiv Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magazines turn to Ukrainian|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/magazines-turn-to-ukrainian-27231.html?flavour=mobile|accessdate=26 November 2014|work=Kyiv Post|date=15 August 2007}}</ref> It was published weekly in Kiev.<ref>{{cite web|title=Full measure of democracy|url=http://www.usubc.org/news/full_measure_williams020808.php|publisher=USUBC|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>
The KP media reported the initial circulation of ''Novynar'' as 15,000 copies in August 2007.<ref name=bne>{{cite news|title=Ukraine daily newsletter|url=http://www.bne.eu/content/file/dispatch-pdf/2007-08-21/58e1-bneUBL210807.pdf|accessdate=26 November 2014|work=BNE|date=21 August 2007}}</ref>
''Novynar'' ceased publication in November 2008 due to financial problems faced.<ref>{{cite news|title=Provincialism in the Diaspora and Ukraine|url=http://risu.org.ua/en/index/monitoring/society_digest/48443/|accessdate=26 November 2014|work=Religious Information Service of Ukraine|date=13 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Media sustainability Index 2009|url=http://www.irex.org/system/files/EE_MSI_09_russ_Ukraine.pdf|work=IREX|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>
