{{Infobox royalty | name = Prince Friedrich Karl | title = | image = File:Fried. Karl of Prussia 4910526328 a7eeec449b o.jpg | caption = | spouse = | issue = | full name = Tassilo Wilhelm Humbert Leopold Friedrich Karl | house = [[House of Hohenzollern]] | father = [[Prince Friedrich Leopold of Prussia]] | mother = [[Princess Louise Sophie of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Augustenburg]] | birth_date = 6 April 1893 | birth_place = [[Glienicke Palace|Schloss Klein-Glienicke]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1917|4|6|1893|4|6|df=y}} | death_place = [[Saint-Étienne-du-Rouvray]] | burial_date = | burial_place = | occupation = | religion = }} {{MedalTop}} {{MedalSport|Men's [[Equestrian at the Summer Olympics|Equestrian]]}} {{MedalBronze|[[1912 Summer Olympics|1912 Stockholm]] | [[Equestrian at the 1912 Summer Olympics – Team jumping|Team jumping]]}} {{MedalBottom}}
{{House of Hohenzollern (Prussia)|frederickwilliam3ggg}}
'''Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia''' (Tassilo Wilhelm Humbert Leopold Friedrich Karl; 6 April 1893 – 6 April 1917) was a [[Germany|German]] [[prince]] and competitive [[Equestrianism|horse rider]] who competed in the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].<ref name="Friedrich Karl, Prince von Preußen">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/vo/friedrich-karl-prince-von-preussen-1.html |title=Friedrich Karl, Prince von Preußen |accessdate=3 August 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>
==Biography== Prince Friedrich Karl was born in [[Jagdschloss Glienicke|Schloss Klein-Glienicke]], [[Potsdam]], [[Berlin]]. He was the son of [[Prince Friedrich Leopold of Prussia]] (1865–1931) and [[Princess Louise Sophie of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Augustenburg]] (1866–1952) and a grandson of [[Prince Frederick Charles of Prussia]].
He was a member of the 1912 German Olympic equestrian team, which won a bronze medal in the [[Equestrian at the 1912 Summer Olympics – Team jumping|team jumping]] event. His horse during the Olympic competition was "Gibson Boy".
He fought in [[World War I]] as an aviator between 1914 and 1917. He commanded ''Fliegerabteilung (Artillerie) 258'', an [[Artillery observer|artillery spotting]] unit, but flew patrols in a single-seat fighter with ''[[Jagdstaffel 2|Jasta Boelcke]]'' whenever possible. During one such patrol on March 21, 1917, he was forced to land because of a bullet in his engine and with a slight wound to his foot. He landed his [[Albatros Flugzeugwerke|Albatros]] aircraft in [[no-man's land]], but while running towards his own lines he was shot in the back and severely wounded by Australian troops.<ref>{{cite web|title=German royal airman’s last fight|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/register/german-royal-airmans-last-fight-xrh2sl3wx|website=The Times|publisher=Times Newspapers Limited|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> He was taken into captivity, where he died from his injuries on 6 April 1917 at [[Saint-Étienne-du-Rouvray]].<ref name="WWI">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/friv/lists.cgi?id=65 |title=Olympians Who Were Killed or Missing in Action or Died as a Result of War |accessdate=3 August 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>
==Regimental Commissions== * 1. Garderegiment zu Fuß (1st Regiment of Foot Guards), Leutnant ''à la suite'' from 1903; Leutnant by 1908.<ref name="autogenerated1908">Schench, G. ''Handbuch über den Königlich Preuβischen Hof und Staat fur das Jahr 1908''. Berlin, Prussia, 1907.</ref> * Fliegerabteilung (Artillerie) 258 (artillery aerial observer squadron), squadron commander, 1917.
==Chivalric Orders<ref name="autogenerated1908"/>== * Knight, [[Order of the Black Eagle]], 1903 * Knight Grand Cross (with Crown), [[Order of the Red Eagle]], 1903 * Knight, First Class, [[Order of the Crown (Prussia)|Prussian Crown Order]], 1903 * Knight Grand Commander, [[House Order of Hohenzollern|Royal House Order of Hohenzollern]], ca 1903
==Military Decorations (1914-1917)== * [[Iron Cross]], Second Class * [[Iron Cross]], First Class * Flugzeugführerabzeichen (Pilot’s qualification badge), ca. 1917
